defs.name: ambient_set_supported
defs.docs: Check whether the running kernel supports the ambient set.

attributes.value: / Check whether the running kernel supports the ambient set.
/ Ambient set was introduced in Linux kernel 4.3. On recent kernels
/ where the ambient set is supported, this will return `Ok`.
/ On a legacy kernel, an `Err` is returned instead.

defs.name: procfs_all_supported
defs.docs: Return the set of all capabilities supported by the running kernel.

attributes.value: / Return the set of all capabilities supported by the running kernel.
/ This requires a mounted `procfs` and a kernel version >= 3.2. By default,
/ it uses `/proc/` as the procfs mountpoint.

defs.name: thread_all_supported
defs.docs: Return the set of all capabilities supported on the current thread.

attributes.value: / Return the set of all capabilities supported on the current thread.
/ This does not require a mounted `procfs`, and it works with any
/ kernel version >= 2.6.25.
/ It internally uses `prctl(2)` and `PR_CAPBSET_READ`; if those are
/ unavailable, this will result in an empty set.
/ Manipulate securebits flags
/ This module exposes methods to get and set per-thread securebits
/ flags, which can be used to disable special handling of capabilities
/ for UID 0 (root).

/ `CAP_CHOWN` (from POSIX)

/ `CAP_DAC_READ_SEARCH` (from POSIX)
/ `CAP_FOWNER` (from POSIX)

/ `CAP_KILL` (from POSIX)
/ `CAP_SETGID` (from POSIX)
/ `CAP_SETUID` (from POSIX)
/ `CAP_SETPCAP` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_MODULE` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_RAWIO` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_CHROOT` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_PTRACE` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_PACCT` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_ADMIN` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_BOOT` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_NICE` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_RESOURCE` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_TIME` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_TTY_CONFIG` (from Linux)
/ `CAP_SYS_MKNOD` (from Linux, >= 2.4)
/ `CAP_LEASE` (from Linux, >= 2.4)
/ `CAP_AUDIT_CONTROL` (from Linux, >= 2.6.11)
/ `CAP_SYSLOG` (from Linux, >= 2.6.37)

/ `CAP_CHECKPOINT_RESTORE` (from Linux, >= 5.9).

defs.docs: Check if a thread contains a capability in a set.

attributes.value: / Check if a thread contains a capability in a set.
/ Check if set `cset` for thread `tid` contains capability `cap`.
/ If `tid` is `None`, this operates on current thread (tid=0).
/ It cannot check Ambient or Bounding capabilities of other processes.

defs.name: read
defs.value: pub fn read(Option<i32>, CapSet) -> Result<CapsHashSet, CapsError>
defs.docs: Return all capabilities in a set for a thread.

attributes.value: / Return all capabilities in a set for a thread.
/ Return current content of set `cset` for thread `tid`.
/ If `tid` is `None`, this operates on current thread (tid=0).
/ It cannot read Ambient or Bounding capabilities of other processes.

defs.name: set
defs.value: pub fn set(Option<i32>, CapSet, &CapsHashSet) -> Result<(), CapsError>
defs.docs: Set a capability set for a thread to a new value.

attributes.value: / Set a capability set for a thread to a new value.
/ All and only capabilities in `value` will be set for set `cset` for thread `tid`.
/ If `tid` is `None`, this operates on current thread (tid=0).
/ It cannot manipulate Ambient set of other processes.
/ Capabilities cannot be set in Bounding set.

defs.name: clear
defs.value: pub fn clear(Option<i32>, CapSet) -> Result<(), CapsError>
defs.docs: Clear all capabilities in a set for a thread.

attributes.value: / Clear all capabilities in a set for a thread.
/ All capabilities will be cleared from set `cset` for thread `tid`.
/ If `tid` is `None`, this operates on current thread (tid=0).
/ It cannot manipulate Ambient or Bounding set of other processes.

defs.docs: Raise a single capability in a set for a thread.

attributes.value: / Raise a single capability in a set for a thread.
/ Capabilities `cap` will be raised from set `cset` of thread `tid`.
/ If `tid` is `None`, this operates on current thread (tid=0).
/ It cannot manipulate Ambient set of other processes.
/ Capabilities cannot be raised in Bounding set.

defs.name: to_canonical
defs.docs: Convert an informal capability name into a canonical form.

attributes.value: / Convert an informal capability name into a canonical form.
/ This converts the input string to uppercase and ensures that it starts with
/ `CAP_`, prepending it if necessary. It performs no validity checks so the
/ output may not represent an actual capability. To check if it is, pass it
/ to [`from_str`].
/ [`from_str`]: enum.Capability.html#method.from_str
